00:14:53.080 --> 00:14:56.700
And then there's the core function that is kind of like you could have written in C or Fortran or something.

00:14:57.400 --> 00:15:00.480
And that wrapper is actually doing all the PyObject stuff.

00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:04.580
It's reaching in and saying, ah, this integer, I'm going to pull out the actual number.

00:15:05.160 --> 00:15:09.540
And oh, this NumPy array, I'm going to reach in and grab the data pointer and pass those

00:15:09.760 --> 00:15:12.360
down into the core where the actual all the math happens.

00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:18.080
And so that is, so the only time you interact with the interpreter is really at the edge.

00:15:19.220 --> 00:15:21.780
And then once you get in there, you try not to touch it ever again.

00:15:21.980 --> 00:15:26.940
Now, NumPy does have a feature that we added some years ago called an object mode block,

00:15:27.040 --> 00:15:28.900
which lets you in the middle of your NoPython code,

00:15:29.380 --> 00:15:32.040
go back and actually start talking to the interpreter again.

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:33.000
Right.

00:15:33.320 --> 00:15:35.180
Maybe use a standard library feature or something.

00:15:35.560 --> 00:15:35.740
Yeah.

00:15:35.820 --> 00:15:39.140
The most common use we've seen is you want a progress bar to update or something.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.020
That's not in your hot loop.

00:15:43.140 --> 00:15:46.020
You don't want to be going back to the interpreter

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:47.860
in something that's really performance critical.

00:15:48.040 --> 00:15:50.860
But inside of a function, you might have parts that are more or less,

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:52.620
one out of a million iterations.

00:15:52.780 --> 00:15:54.460
I want to go update the progress bar or something.

00:15:55.259 --> 00:15:56.300
That's totally valid.

00:15:56.840 --> 00:15:57.880
And you can do that with Numba.

00:15:58.140 --> 00:16:00.420
There's a way to get back to the interpreter if you really need to.

00:16:01.340 --> 00:16:01.740
Okay.

00:16:03.480 --> 00:16:07.180
Yeah, and it says it takes and translates Python functions

00:16:07.290 --> 00:16:11.080
to optimize machine code at runtime, which is cool.

00:16:11.170 --> 00:16:12.760
So that makes deploying it super easy.

00:16:13.560 --> 00:16:16.040
And you don't have to have compiled wheels for it and stuff.

00:16:16.520 --> 00:16:19.000
Using industry standard LLVM compilers.

00:16:19.860 --> 00:16:24.220
And then similar speeds to C is in Fortran.

00:16:24.740 --> 00:16:25.060
Yeah.

00:16:25.420 --> 00:16:32.500
Which is awesome, but also has implications, if I can speak.

00:16:33.060 --> 00:16:40.800
For example, when I came to Python, I was blown away that I could just have integers as big as I want.

00:16:41.320 --> 00:16:43.220
If I keep adding to them, they just get bigger and bigger.

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:49.040
Billions, bazillions of bits of accuracy.

00:16:49.980 --> 00:16:52.840
it came from C++ and C#,

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:56.060
and where you explicitly said it's an N32,

00:16:56.280 --> 00:16:58.120
it's an N64, it's a double,

00:16:58.220 --> 00:17:01.100
and these all had ranges of valid numbers,

00:17:01.260 --> 00:17:03.200
and then you got weird wraparounds,

00:17:03.460 --> 00:17:05.120
and maybe you create an unsigned one,

00:17:05.120 --> 00:17:06.060
so you can get a little bit bigger.

00:17:06.740 --> 00:17:10.280
I suspect that you may fall victim

00:17:10.480 --> 00:17:13.880
or be subjected to these types of limitations

00:17:14.280 --> 00:17:17.459
without realizing them in Python if you add NGedit

00:17:17.819 --> 00:17:19.079
because you're back in that land, right?

00:17:19.120 --> 00:17:22.660
Right. Or do you guys magic to allow us?

00:17:22.750 --> 00:17:24.319
We do not, we do not handle the big integer,

00:17:24.589 --> 00:17:26.220
which is what you're describing as sort of that,

00:17:26.360 --> 00:17:27.780
that integer that can grow without bound.

00:17:29.620 --> 00:17:32.420
Because our target audience is very familiar with NumPy,

00:17:32.640 --> 00:17:35.180
NumPy looks at numbers sort of the way you're,

00:17:35.500 --> 00:17:37.320
you described from C++ and other languages.

00:17:37.780 --> 00:17:39.000
The D type and all that stuff, right?

00:17:39.240 --> 00:17:42.720
Yeah. NumPy arrays always have a fixed size integer and you get to pick what

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:45.840
that is, but it has to be eight, 16, 32, 64.

00:17:47.060 --> 00:17:49.640
Some machines can handle bigger, but that it is fixed.

00:17:49.800 --> 00:17:55.080
And so once you've locked that in, you can't over, if you, if you go too big, you'll just

00:17:55.280 --> 00:17:56.120
wrap around and overflow.

00:17:56.680 --> 00:18:01.860
And so, yeah, so that limitation is definitely present again in Numba, but fortunately, NumPy

00:18:01.980 --> 00:18:03.680
users are already familiar with thinking that way.

00:18:04.220 --> 00:18:07.260
So it isn't an additional constraint on them too much.

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:08.480
Right.

00:18:09.100 --> 00:18:09.220
Okay.

