Yes, that's true.

00:18:32.980 --> 00:18:33.540
What an array is.

00:18:34.140 --> 00:18:38.760
I would say generally, yeah, usually the go-to I talk to about is a numpy array.

00:18:39.080 --> 00:18:40.340
So it has a shape.

00:18:41.020 --> 00:18:43.060
The nice thing, you know, numpy arrays can be multidimensional.

00:18:43.560 --> 00:18:45.820
So you can represent a lot of complex data that way.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.520
But within an array, there's a fixed element size.

00:18:50.300 --> 00:18:51.580
That element could be a record.

00:18:52.480 --> 00:18:56.340
So if you want for every cell in your array to store maybe a set of numbers or a pair of numbers,

00:18:56.500 --> 00:18:59.280
you can do that with custom D types and things.

00:19:00.080 --> 00:19:01.140
And Numba will understand that.

00:19:02.120 --> 00:19:04.540
But that's basically, that's the ideal data structure.

00:19:04.740 --> 00:19:09.360
Numba does have, we added support a couple years ago for other data structures

00:19:09.490 --> 00:19:13.140
because the downside to a Numpy array is that it's fixed size.

00:19:13.480 --> 00:19:17.120
Once you make it, you can't append to it like you can a Python list.

00:19:17.660 --> 00:19:22.280
So Numba does have support for both what we call typed lists and typed dictionaries.

00:19:22.820 --> 00:19:30.960
So these are sort of special cases of lists and dictionaries in Python where in the case of a list, every element in the list has the same type.

00:19:32.260 --> 00:19:36.060
Or in the case of a dictionary, the keys are all the same type and the values are all the same type.

00:19:37.040 --> 00:19:47.100
And those cover a lot of the cases where, again, when users want to make things where they don't know how long it's going to be, you're going to append in the algorithm.

00:19:47.900 --> 00:19:51.700
A list is a much more natural thing than an umpire array where you might over allocate or something.

00:19:53.100 --> 00:19:59.380
And dictionaries, our dictionary implementation is basically taken straight from CPython's dictionary implementation.

00:19:59.560 --> 00:20:03.220
So it's very tuned and very fast in the same way CPython's is.

00:20:03.620 --> 00:20:06.340
We just had to modify it a little bit to add this type information.

00:20:07.080 --> 00:20:13.320
but it's um it's really good for kind of look up random items uh kind of stuff so those are

00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:17.920
available as additional data structures in addition to yeah and to use those i would say

00:20:19.420 --> 00:20:26.200
from number import something something like this yeah they're they're they're a new type in the

00:20:26.580 --> 00:20:31.659
yeah in the in the docs i'll show you you can sort of import a typed list as a special class

00:20:32.100 --> 00:20:32.660
that you can create.

00:20:33.070 --> 00:20:34.660
The downside, by the way, is that,

00:20:35.550 --> 00:20:36.860
and the reason we have those

00:20:37.120 --> 00:20:37.940
and we don't just take,

00:20:38.360 --> 00:20:40.020
historically nobody used to try

00:20:40.220 --> 00:20:41.640
and let you pass in a Python list,

00:20:42.240 --> 00:20:45.060
is that wrapper function would have to go recursively

00:20:45.260 --> 00:20:46.280
through the list of lists of lists

00:20:46.290 --> 00:20:47.100
of whatever you might have

00:20:47.500 --> 00:20:48.940
and pop out all of the elements

00:20:49.860 --> 00:20:53.020
into some format that wasn't all PyObjects

00:20:53.460 --> 00:20:54.480
so that the no Python code

00:20:54.620 --> 00:20:55.620
could manipulate them quickly.

00:20:56.300 --> 00:20:57.540
And then how do you put it all back

00:20:57.660 --> 00:21:00.220
if you modify that sort of shadow data structure?

00:21:01.080 --> 00:21:06.520
And so what we realized is that was confusing people and actually added a lot of overhead and calling functions took too long.

00:21:07.060 --> 00:21:13.400
So we instead went up a level and said, OK, we're going to make a new kind of list that you at the interpreter level can opt into for your algorithm.

00:21:14.340 --> 00:21:17.540
And so accessing that list from Python is slower than a Python list.

00:21:18.190 --> 00:21:21.340
But accessing it from Numba is like 100 times faster.

00:21:22.520 --> 00:21:26.380
So you kind of have to decide while I'm in this mode,

00:21:27.180 --> 00:21:29.260
I'm optimizing for numbers performance,

00:21:29.600 --> 00:21:31.240
not for the Python interpreter performance.

00:21:32.160 --> 00:21:34.420
Which is reasonable often, I'd imagine,

00:21:34.600 --> 00:21:36.200
because this is the part you found to be slow.

00:21:36.840 --> 00:21:38.460
Yeah, that's the trade-off you make.

00:21:38.510 --> 00:21:39.080
And so, yeah.

00:21:39.580 --> 00:21:41.640
So we would not suggest people use typelist

00:21:41.740 --> 00:21:43.600
just in random places in their program.

00:21:43.680 --> 00:21:45.120
I heard this is fast.

00:21:45.400 --> 00:21:47.940
So we're just going to replace all, like, new rule,

00:21:48.600 --> 00:21:49.840
bracket bracket is disallowed.

00:21:49.840 --> 00:21:50.940
We're now using this one, right?

