00:27:09.480 --> 00:27:11.360
One more thing I want to ask you about here before we go on.

00:27:11.860 --> 00:27:15.620
This has a Cython feel to it.

00:27:15.780 --> 00:27:18.440
Can you compare and contrast Numba to Cython?

00:27:19.240 --> 00:27:19.560
Yeah.

00:27:19.940 --> 00:27:29.260
So Cython sort of requires you to put in some type information in order to be able to generate C code that is more efficient.

00:27:29.960 --> 00:27:32.480
Numba is mainly focused on type inference.

00:27:33.200 --> 00:27:36.320
So we try to figure out all the types in your function

00:27:36.880 --> 00:27:38.340
based on the types of the inputs.

00:27:39.020 --> 00:27:41.900
And so in general, although Numba has places

00:27:41.980 --> 00:27:43.240
where you can put type annotations,

00:27:43.580 --> 00:27:45.360
we generally discourage people from doing it

00:27:45.740 --> 00:27:49.200
because we find that it adds work and is error prone

00:27:49.260 --> 00:27:50.920
and doesn't really help the performance in the end.

00:27:51.320 --> 00:27:54.460
Numba will figure out all the types directly.

00:27:55.160 --> 00:27:57.860
And so when it compiles it, if it comes in,

00:27:57.900 --> 00:27:59.660
if you call it twice with different types,

00:27:59.820 --> 00:28:00.460
does it just say,

00:28:00.900 --> 00:28:02.020
well, now we're going to need

00:28:03.040 --> 00:28:05.580
this version of the function underscore strings list

00:28:05.710 --> 00:28:07.060
rather than integers list or something?

00:28:07.320 --> 00:28:09.880
Yeah, every number compiled function

00:28:10.090 --> 00:28:11.320
actually contains a dispatcher

00:28:11.420 --> 00:28:12.660
that will look at the argument types

00:28:12.690 --> 00:28:13.540
and pick the right one.

00:28:14.500 --> 00:28:16.100
And it's at pretty high granularity.

00:28:16.700 --> 00:28:17.120
For example,

00:28:18.320 --> 00:28:20.280
people who are familiar with multidimensional arrays

00:28:20.360 --> 00:28:21.320
in like Fortran and C

00:28:21.900 --> 00:28:23.880
know that they lay out the rows and columns

00:28:23.990 --> 00:28:24.640
in a different order,

00:28:25.120 --> 00:28:27.840
which has impact on how you do loops and stuff

00:28:28.270 --> 00:28:29.940
for kind of to maximize locality.

00:28:30.800 --> 00:28:32.580
Numba can tell the difference between those two cases

00:28:33.100 --> 00:28:35.420
and will generate different code for those two cases.

00:28:35.540 --> 00:28:35.700
Wow.

00:28:36.060 --> 00:28:39.480
So this is something you as the user don't want to even know.

