Yeah, you essentially have a compiler

00:34:11.679 --> 00:34:13.780
from a bunch of little recipes that are,

00:34:14.020 --> 00:34:16.679
if I do this pattern, sub in this machine code,

00:34:16.840 --> 00:34:19.620
fill in these blanks, and you just have a table of them.

00:34:19.659 --> 00:34:22.659
So the challenge there is that there is

00:34:22.659 --> 00:34:25.560
a combinatorial explosion again of how many different,

00:34:26.260 --> 00:34:30.679
a full-blown compiler like LLVM has a bunch of rules.

00:34:31.060 --> 00:34:31.760
It's rule-based.

00:34:32.120 --> 00:34:36.360
And so it's saying, if I see this pattern, I do this replacement and it keeps doing all of this.

00:34:36.440 --> 00:34:39.659
And then at the end, it says, OK, now I'm going to generate my machine code from that.

00:34:40.020 --> 00:34:48.000
Those transformations. If I don't have LLVM at runtime, I have to kind of figure out what are the best templates up front, put them in this table.

00:34:48.360 --> 00:34:55.820
And then, you know, so this is where honestly looking at different usage patterns will probably be a huge help is in practice.

00:34:56.760 --> 00:35:00.400
