01:05:56.360 --> 01:05:58.020
And not the package installing thing,

01:05:58.020 --> 01:06:01.940
but the JIG compiler, PYPY, PYPY.

01:06:02.600 --> 01:06:04.000
Sometimes phonetically, like over audio,

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:05.280
that's hard to tell.

01:06:05.580 --> 01:06:05.800
Yes, yeah, yeah.

01:06:05.940 --> 01:06:07.800
So he's been thinking about this stuff for a very long time.

01:06:08.700 --> 01:06:17.740
And his sort of key insight that at least clicked in my head was that Python is hard to compile because it is so dynamic.

01:06:18.620 --> 01:06:25.240
I can, in principle, modify the attributes, like even the functions of a class at any point in the execution of the program.

01:06:25.670 --> 01:06:26.880
I can marquee patch anything.

01:06:27.200 --> 01:06:33.000
can do this. This dynamicness is really great for making kind of magical metaprogramming libraries

01:06:33.280 --> 01:06:38.860
that do do amazing things with very little typing, but it makes compiling them really hard

01:06:40.040 --> 01:06:44.940
because you don't get to ever say, okay, this can't ever change. and so what he's been

01:06:45.060 --> 01:06:50.380
trying to do with a project called spy, which he gave a talk on at PyCon 2024, but I think the,

01:06:50.800 --> 01:06:56.500
the recordings aren't up yet for that. and so there isn't a, I don't think there's a public

01:06:56.520 --> 01:07:02.820
page on it, but he does have a talk on it. And because I think they've got like the keynotes up,

01:07:03.420 --> 01:07:10.580
but the key kind of insight for me for spy was to recognize that in a typical Python program,

01:07:11.240 --> 01:07:16.280
all the dynamic meta programming happens at the beginning. You're doing things like data classes,

01:07:16.480 --> 01:07:22.180
generating stuff and all kinds of things like that. And then there's a phase where that stops.

01:07:23.480 --> 01:07:27.040
And so if we could define a sort of variant of Python

01:07:27.780 --> 01:07:29.780
where those two phases were really clear,

01:07:31.180 --> 01:07:34.260
then you would get all of the dynamic expressiveness,

01:07:34.420 --> 01:07:36.220
almost all the dynamic expressiveness of Python,

01:07:36.980 --> 01:07:39.040
but still have the ability to then feed that

01:07:39.260 --> 01:07:42.000
into a compiler tool chain and get a binary.

01:07:42.780 --> 01:07:45.660
So this is super early R&D experimental work,

01:07:45.700 --> 01:07:49.120
but I think that's a really great way to approach it

01:07:49.280 --> 01:07:51.760
because often there's always been this tension of,

01:07:52.540 --> 01:07:54.940
well, if I make Python statically compilable,

01:07:55.110 --> 01:07:58.000
is it just C with different keywords?

01:07:59.460 --> 01:08:01.220
Do I lose the thing I loved about Python,

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:04.280
which was how quickly I could express my idea?

01:08:04.560 --> 01:08:06.120
And so this is, again,

01:08:06.320 --> 01:08:07.820
to having your cake and eating it too.

01:08:07.980 --> 01:08:10.320
This is trying to find a way to split that difference

01:08:11.080 --> 01:08:13.860
in a way that lets us get most of the benefits of both sides.

